    task: "Build a FastAPI app with layered DI: DB session, auth header, rate limiter — all as Depends(). Understand how Starlette ASGI handles requests. Add middleware.",
    depth: "ASGI, middleware chain, DI graph, Starlette internals",
    source: "FastAPI docs advanced | Starlette source | testdriven.io/fastapi",
    whyMatters: "FastAPI is built on Starlette which is an ASGI framework. ASGI (Asynchronous Server Gateway Interface) is the protocol that connects a web server (like uvicorn) to your Python app. Dependency Injection in FastAPI is how you share resources like database sessions, authenticated users, and rate limiters across request handlers without repeating yourself. Understanding this lets you build large APIs that are maintainable — not a pile of copy-pasted boilerplate.",
    howToDoIt: "Build a FastAPI app with three Depends() layers: get_db() that yields a fake database session, get_current_user() that depends on get_db() and reads an Authorization header, and check_rate_limit() that depends on get_current_user() and checks a request counter. Chain them: a route that depends on all three. Then add a middleware (not a Depends) that logs every request's path, method, and response time. Understand the difference: middleware runs for EVERY request, Depends runs only when declared.",
    watchOutFor: "Depends() creates a new dependency instance per request by default — for database sessions this is correct. But if you use a singleton (like a Redis client), don't put it in Depends — just initialize it at module level. Also: middleware and exception handlers have different scopes. A 500 error in middleware won't be caught by your HTTPException handler.",
    doneWhen: "You can draw the dependency graph for your app. You know what ASGI is at a conceptual level. You can explain why Depends() is better than global variables for request-scoped resources.",
