    source: "Redis docs | cloudflare.com/blog/counting-things-a-lot | stripe.com/blog/rate-limiters",
    whyMatters: "Rate limiting prevents a single user or attacker from overwhelming your API. Token bucket is the algorithm Stripe, Cloudflare, and most APIs use: imagine a bucket that fills with tokens at a fixed rate. Each request takes a token. When the bucket is empty, requests are rejected. Implementing this correctly in a distributed system (multiple API servers) requires atomic operations in Redis — which means Lua scripts. This is intermediate-to-advanced Redis, and it's what real production rate limiters look like.",
    howToDoIt: "In Redis, write a Lua script that implements token bucket atomically: it takes bucket_key, max_tokens, refill_rate, cost as arguments. It reads the current token count and last_refill time, calculates tokens earned since last refill, adds them (capped at max_tokens), subtracts cost, and returns 1 (allowed) or 0 (denied). Call it with redis.eval(). Add it as FastAPI middleware that reads a user ID from the request and applies the limit. Return a 429 response with Retry-After header when limited. Test it with 20 concurrent requests using asyncio.",
    watchOutFor: "Lua scripts in Redis run atomically — nothing can interrupt them between reads and writes. This is critical for race conditions. Without Lua, you'd need WATCH/MULTI/EXEC transactions, which are harder to get right. Also: rate limit by user ID, not IP address — IPs are shared in corporate networks, and one user behind NAT would block everyone.",
    doneWhen: "Your rate limiter correctly handles concurrent requests without race conditions (test with threading). It returns the right headers. You can explain why a non-atomic implementation would have a race condition.",
