    task: "Write an OpenAPI 3.1 spec manually for a resource API. Generate FastAPI stub from it. Validate your live API against the spec with schemathesis. Version a breaking change.",
    depth: "Contract-first, versioning strategies, spec testing",
    source: "swagger.io/specification | schemathesis.readthedocs.io",
    whyMatters: "Spec-first API design means you write the OpenAPI specification BEFORE you write code. This forces you to think about the contract — what endpoints exist, what parameters they take, what they return — before getting distracted by implementation. It also lets you auto-generate client code, run contract tests, and catch breaking changes. At companies like Stripe, the API spec IS the product — everything else is implementation detail.",
    howToDoIt: "Write an OpenAPI 3.1 YAML spec for a Task API: CRUD for tasks, with pagination, filtering by status, and a PATCH endpoint for partial update. Define schemas with required fields, nullable fields, enums for status. Then use FastAPI to implement it — make your FastAPI app match the spec, not the other way around. Install schemathesis and run it against your live server: it generates hundreds of test cases from your spec and finds edge cases you didn't think of. Then simulate a breaking change (rename a field) and see how clients break.",
    watchOutFor: "A breaking change is: removing a field, renaming a field, changing a type, making an optional field required. A non-breaking change is: adding a new optional field, adding a new endpoint. Version your API (v1, v2) when you need to make breaking changes — never silently break clients.",
    doneWhen: "schemathesis found at least one bug you didn't know about (it almost always does). You can explain what makes a change 'breaking' vs 'non-breaking'. Your spec and implementation match — no drift.",
