    source: "rfc-editor.org/rfc/rfc7807 (Problem Details) | FastAPI exception handling",
    whyMatters: "Most APIs handle errors badly: they return a 500 with a Python stack trace (leaks implementation details and is a security risk), or they return {'error': 'something went wrong'} with no useful information. Good error handling is a design decision: every error has a code, a human message, a developer message, and an HTTP status. Retryable errors are different from non-retryable ones. This day is about treating errors as first-class citizens of your API design.",
    howToDoIt: "Design an error taxonomy: 4 categories (validation, authentication, not_found, server_error), each with sub-codes (e.g. validation.required_field, auth.token_expired). Implement a global exception handler in FastAPI that catches all exceptions and returns RFC 7807 Problem Details format: {type, title, status, detail, instance}. Never include Python tracebacks in responses — log them server-side only. Build an error middleware that classifies errors as retryable (500, 503) or non-retryable (400, 401, 404) and adds a Retry-After header for retryable ones.",
    watchOutFor: "RFC 7807 (Problem Details for HTTP APIs) is the standard format for API errors — learn it, use it. Also: 422 Unprocessable Entity is for validation errors (FastAPI uses this by default), 400 Bad Request is for malformed requests (wrong JSON syntax). These are often confused. And: NEVER return 200 with an error body — this breaks every HTTP client, logging system, and monitoring tool.",
    doneWhen: "Your API never returns a Python traceback. Every error response follows RFC 7807 format. You can look at any error response and immediately know if you should retry or not.",
