    topic: "API Security Hardening",
    task: "Implement: input validation at boundary, mass assignment protection, CORS properly (not *), secrets in env not code, SQL injection via raw query test+fix.",
    depth: "OWASP top 10, input validation layers, CORS headers",
    source: "OWASP API Security Top 10 | owasp.org/API-Security",
    whyMatters: "API security is not something you add at the end. The OWASP API Security Top 10 is the definitive list of how APIs get hacked — and most vulnerabilities are not sophisticated attacks, they're basic mistakes. Mass assignment happens when you blindly pass user input to a database model. IDOR (Insecure Direct Object Reference) happens when you fetch /users/123 without checking if the logged-in user is allowed to see user 123. SQL injection via ORM happens when you use raw() queries with string formatting. This day makes you think like an attacker.",
    howToDoIt: "Build a FastAPI app with two intentional vulnerabilities: (1) Mass assignment — a User model where you do User(**request.body) and the request includes is_admin=true which gets saved. (2) IDOR — GET /orders/{order_id} that returns the order without checking if it belongs to the current user. Now fix both: use explicit field mapping (never **unpack user input into models), add ownership check on every resource access. Then configure CORS properly: instead of allow_origins=['*'], specify exact origins. Finally, store your JWT secret in an env var, never hardcoded.",
    watchOutFor: "CORS is enforced by browsers, not servers — an attacker using curl or Postman bypasses CORS entirely. CORS protects users from malicious websites, not from direct API attacks. Also: the most dangerous OWASP vulnerabilities (Broken Object Level Authorization = IDOR) are logic bugs — no scanner finds them automatically. You have to think through every endpoint: 'can user A access user B's data?'",
    doneWhen: "You can find the IDOR vulnerability in your own code before fixing it. You understand why allow_origins=['*'] is dangerous. You've tested mass assignment and seen it work — then prevented it.",
