    whyMatters: "Most developers use Git as a save button — commit, push, done. But Git is actually a content-addressable filesystem — every file, every commit, every tree is stored as a SHA1-hashed object. Understanding this means you'll never be scared of git rebase, git reset, or a detached HEAD state. You'll understand what 'merge conflict' actually means at the byte level. This knowledge separates engineers who use Git from engineers who understand Git.",
    howToDoIt: "Explore your .git folder: look at .git/HEAD (it's just a text file pointing to a branch), .git/refs/heads/main (a SHA1 hash), .git/objects/ (all your content, hashed). Run git cat-file -t to see the type (commit, tree, blob). Run git cat-file -p to see the content. Now create a file, stage it, and use git cat-file to see the blob object created. Then: practice git reflog (your safety net — shows every action including 'deleted' commits), git rebase -i HEAD~3 (interactive rebase to squash/reorder commits), git bisect (binary search for the commit that introduced a bug).",
    watchOutFor: "git reset --hard is destructive — it discards uncommitted changes permanently. git reset --soft is safe — it unstages commits but keeps your files. Always check git status before a reset. Also: rebasing rewrites history — never rebase commits that have been pushed to a shared branch. This is the rule that saves teams from chaos.",
