    whyMatters: "PostgreSQL is the best general-purpose relational database, and most developers use 5% of its capabilities. B-tree indexes are what you add to speed up WHERE clauses. GIN indexes are for full-text search and JSONB columns. Partial indexes index only rows matching a condition (e.g., only active users) — much smaller and faster for filtered queries. EXPLAIN ANALYZE is PostgreSQL's execution plan tool — it shows you exactly how a query runs and where time is spent. VACUUM is how Postgres reclaims space from deleted rows (its MVCC architecture keeps old row versions around).",
    howToDoIt: "Create a users table with 100k rows (use generate_series in SQL). Write this query: SELECT * FROM users WHERE email LIKE '%@gmail.com' — run EXPLAIN ANALYZE, note the cost. Add a GIN index with pg_trgm extension for LIKE queries: CREATE EXTENSION pg_trgm; CREATE INDEX USING GIN(email gin_trgm_ops). Rerun EXPLAIN ANALYZE — compare costs. Then create an index only on active users: CREATE INDEX ON users(created_at) WHERE is_active = true. Write a query that benefits from this. Finally, delete 50k rows and run VACUUM ANALYZE manually — watch pg_stat_user_tables show dead tuples decrease.",
    watchOutFor: "EXPLAIN shows the plan. EXPLAIN ANALYZE actually RUNS the query (don't use ANALYZE on production with slow queries — it will be slow). The 'cost' numbers are not milliseconds — they're relative units. What matters is comparing before/after the same query. A Seq Scan isn't always bad — for small tables or queries returning most rows, it's faster than an index scan.",
